import seaborn as sns

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Histograms for predictors and happiness_score
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, len(predictors) + 1, figsize=(18, 4))
for idx, col in enumerate(predictors + ['happiness_score']):
    sns.histplot(df[col], ax=axes[idx], kde=True, color='skyblue')
    axes[idx].set_title(f'Histogram of {col}')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Boxplots for predictors vs happiness_score
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, len(predictors), figsize=(18, 4))
for idx, col in enumerate(predictors):
    sns.boxplot(x=df[col], y=df['happiness_score'], ax=axes[idx])
    axes[idx].set_title(f'Boxplot: {col} vs happiness_score')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Scatterplots for predictors vs happiness_score
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, len(predictors), figsize=(18, 4))
for idx, col in enumerate(predictors):
    sns.scatterplot(x=df[col], y=df['happiness_score'], ax=axes[idx], alpha=0.5)
    axes[idx].set_title(f'Scatterplot: {col} vs happiness_score')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Pairplot for all predictors and happiness_score
sns.pairplot(df[predictors + ['happiness_score']], diag_kind='kde')
plt.suptitle('Pairplot of Predictors and Happiness Score', y=1.02)
plt.show()

# Correlation heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(df[predictors + ['happiness_score']].corr(), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f')
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap')
plt.show()

# Feature Selection using Variance Threshold
from sklearn.feature_selection import VarianceThreshold
    # Initialize VarianceThreshold with a chosen threshold
    # For example, threshold=0.1 to remove features with variance less than 0.1
selector = VarianceThreshold(threshold=.1)

    # Fit the selector to the DataFrame and transform it
    # Note: VarianceThreshold expects a NumPy array, so use df.values
df_reduced_array = selector.fit_transform(df)
    # Get a boolean mask of selected features
selected_features_mask = selector.get_support()

    # Get the names of the selected features
selected_feature_names = df.columns[selected_features_mask]

    # Create a new DataFrame with only the selected features
df_reduced = pd.DataFrame(df_reduced_array, columns=selected_feature_names)

print("\nReduced DataFrame after Variance Thresholding:")
print(df_reduced)
print("\nRetained Features:", df_reduced.columns.tolist())

In[59]:
from scipy.stats import pearsonr

results = {}
target = 'happiness_score'

for feature in additional_features:
    r, p = pearsonr(df[feature], df[target])
    results[feature] = {'pearson_r': r, 'p_value': p}

for feature, stats in results.items():
    print(f"{feature}: Pearson r = {stats['pearson_r']:.4f}, p-value = {stats['p_value']:.4g}")

In[66]:
# Rank features by absolute Pearson correlation with `happiness_score`
# Requires existing `results` dict in the notebook.
ranked = sorted(results.items(), key=lambda kv: abs(float(kv[1]["pearson_r"])), reverse=True)
for i, (feat, stats) in enumerate(ranked, 1):
    r = float(stats["pearson_r"])
    p = float(stats["p_value"])
    sig = p < 0.05
    direction = "positive" if r > 0 else "negative"
    print(f"{i}. {feat}: r={r:.4f} (abs={abs(r):.4f}), p={p:.2e}, significant={sig}, direction={direction}")
